               <msContents>
                  <summary> The <title>Pandnāmah</title> (Book of Advice), or <title>Karīmā</title>
                     (O Merciful!), a highly-popular book of ethical exhortations and sage advice
                     that while erroneously attributed to Saʻdī (d. 1292), enjoyed broad circulation
                     since at least 150 years after his death. Renowned Delhi scribe
                        Sayyid Abū’l-Ḥasan Raz̤avī (fl. late 18th-early 19th c.), known as 'Mīr
                        Kallan', completed this copy in <date calendar="Gregorian" when="1800"
                           >1800</date>. A leading student of master calligrapher Muḥamamd Ḥafīẓ
                        Khān (d. 1780), this volume features elaborately illuminated opening pages.
                        Apparently expertly repaired by a stationer-copyist who replaced four
                        missing folios, then had it rebound in a hybrid British-Indian style.
                  </summary>
                  <msItem xml:id="Persian_MS_572-item1">
                     <author key="person_100206721" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/100206721/" role="dub"
                        cert="low">
                        <persName xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" type="standard">Saʻdī</persName>
                        <persName xml:lang="fa">سعدى</persName>
                     </author>
                     <title xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" key="work_20151" change="#ids-cleanup">Pandnāmah
                        (Book of Wisdom)</title>
                     <title xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" type="alt" key="work_20151"
                        change="#ids-cleanup">Pand'nāmah</title>
                     <title xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" type="alt" key="work_2361">Karīmā</title>
                     <title xml:lang="fa" key="work_20151" change="#ids-cleanup">پند نامه</title>
                     <title xml:lang="fa" type="alt" key="work_20151" change="#ids-cleanup"
                        >پندنامه</title>
                     <title xml:lang="fa" type="alt" key="work_20151">کریما</title>
                     <editor role="scr">
                        <persName type="standard" xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" key="person_f6479"> Sayyid
                           Abū-l-Ḥasan Raz̤avī <foreign xml:lang="fa">سید ابو الحسن رضوی
                           </foreign></persName>, known as <addName type="pen-name"
                           key="person_f6479">Mīr Kallan <foreign xml:lang="fa">میر
                              کَلَّن</foreign></addName>
                     </editor>
                     <incipit type="basmalla" xml:lang="fa"><locus from="1b" to="1b"> برگ ۱پ (folio
                           1b):</locus> کریما ببخشای بر حال ما * که هستیم اسیر کمند هوا</incipit>
                     <explicit xml:lang="fa"><locus from="17b" to="17b"> برگ ۱٧پ (folio 17b):</locus> منه دل
                        برین دهر ناپایدار * ز سعدی همین یک سخن گوشدار</explicit>
                     <colophon xml:lang="fa"><locus from="18b" to="19a">برگه‌های ۱۷پ-۱۸ر (folio
                           17b–18a):</locus> برگهای ۱۷پ-۱۸ر: بتاریخ چهارم شهر ربیع الثانی سنه ۱۲۱۵
                        یکهزار و دوصد و پانزده هجرة النبی صلی الله علیه وآله و اصحاب المرصلین
                        االکاتب سید ابو الحسن رضوی عرف میر کَلَّن [برگ ۱۸ر] غفر الله تعالی ذنوبه و
                        ستر عیوبه مطابق سنه۴۲ چهل و دویم جلوس ممنت مانوس ابو المظفر محمد شاه عالم
                        پادشاه غازی خلد لله ملکهه سلطانه.</colophon>
                     <colophon xml:lang="en">Completed by <persName type="standard">Sayyid Abū
                           al-Ḥasan Raz̤avī</persName>, known as '<addName type="pen-name"
                           key="person_f6479">Mīr Kallan</addName>', probably in <placeName
                           cert="high">Delhi, India</placeName> on <date calendar="#Hijri-qamari"
                           when="1800-08-25">4 Rabi' II 1215 AH (25 August 1800 CE)</date>, equal to
                        the 42nd regnal year of <persName type="standard"
                           ref=" http://viaf.org/viaf/70169499" key="person_70169499">Shāh ʻĀlam II
                           (1728-1806), Emperor of Hindustan (1760–1806)</persName>.</colophon>
                     <textLang mainLang="fa">Persian</textLang>
                     <note><persName type="standard" role="trl"
                        ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/122281196" key="person_122281196"> Francis
                        Gladwin (1744/5–1812)</persName>
                        first translated it into English in <date calendar="Gregorian"
                           when="1788">1788</date> intended as a textbook to instruct British
                        civil servants of the East India Company in Persian. The final two lines differ from his edition, as does the final word in <persName
                           type="standard" role="trl" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/52471839"
                           key="person_52471839"> Arthur Wollaston's (1842–1922)</persName>
                        <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1908">1908</date> version, as noted by
                           <persName type="standard" role="trl" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/238066790"
                           key="person_238066790">G. M. Wickens (1918–2006)</persName> in the
                        introduction of his translation. The scribe, <persName type="standard">Sayyid Abū
                           al-Ḥasan Raz̤avī</persName>, known as '<addName type="pen-name"
                              key="person_f6479">Mīr Kallan</addName>' emigrated to India with his family, presumably from Iran to Delhi, where he studied under master <persName>Muḥammad Ḥafīẓ Khān (d. 1779–80)</persName></note>
                  </msItem>
               </msContents>
               <physDesc>
                  <objectDesc form="codex">
                     <supportDesc material="paper">
                        <support><p>The textblock contains two types of laid
                           <material>paper</material>, probably handmade in <placeName ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000208">India</placeName>; with the majority of the text
                              written on a medium-weight <material>
                              paper</material>, and conjugate folios 3–7 and 12–16 replaced
                              with a comparatively thin, externally sized, and highly polished stock.</p>
                           <p>Flyleaves of <material>mould-made paper</material> watermarked with a
                                 <watermark>lion clutching a shield emblazoned with the St George's
                                 Cross, the English flag</watermark> dated <date
                                 calendar="#Gregorian" when="1863">1863</date>.</p></support>
                        <extent>
                           <measure unit="folios" quantity="18">18 folios (ii+18+ii)</measure>
                           <dimensions type="leaf" unit="mm">
                              <height>161</height>
                              <width>101</width>
                           </dimensions>
                           <dimensions type="written" unit="mm">
                              <height>105</height>
                              <width>57</width>
                           </dimensions>
                        </extent>
                        <foliation>
                           <p>Foliation marked at top-centre of the a sides in Hindu-Arabic
                              numerals.</p>
                        </foliation>
                        <collation>1IV(8)1V(18). Two sections: a quaternion and quinternion.<p>
                              <catchwords>Catchwords inscribed at the lower left corners of the b
                                 sidesk throughout.</catchwords></p></collation>
                        <condition>
                           <p>Handle with caution: extensive repairs to the gutters and lower
                              margins of the text after apparent water damage. The first and last
                              folios are heavily tipped to the flyleaves in the gutter and so do not
                              open flat. Green verdigris marginal rulings on folios <locus from="5" to="5">5</locus>, <locus from="6" to="6">6</locus>, and <locus from="8" to="11">8–11</locus>, and
                              <locus from="13" to="13">13</locus> are breaking half way down the inner margin.</p>
                        </condition>
                     </supportDesc>
                     <layoutDesc>
                        <layout columns="2" ruledLines="7" n="mistara">Written in 2 columns, with 7
                           lines per page. Ruled with a <hi rend="italic">misṭarah</hi> hand guide.</layout>
                     </layoutDesc>
                  </objectDesc>
                  <handDesc>
                     <handNote scope="major" script="nasta_liq" medium="ink">
                        <desc>The majority of the text is written in nasta‘liq script in black
                              <material>ink</material>, in a comparatively heavier hand transcribed
                           by <persName key="person_f6479">Sayyid Abū al-Ḥasan Raz̤avī</persName>,
                           known as known as '<addName type="pen-name" key="person_f6479">'Mīr
                              Kallan</addName>' with <hi rend="italic">basmallah</hi> in <material>blue</material>, and
                           chapter headings in <material>red</material>.</desc>
                     </handNote>
                     <handNote scope="minor" script="nasta_liq" medium="ink">
                        <desc>Replaced folios 3–7 and 12–16 are written in a more refined nasta‘liq
                           hand in <material>black</material>, with chapter headings in <material>red</material>.</desc>
                     </handNote>
                  </handDesc>
                  <decoDesc>
                     <decoNote type="carpetPage"><p>A fully illuminated double-page opening on
                           folios <locus from="1b" to="2a">1b to 2a</locus> appears executed in the
                           early nineteenth century but recalls earlier sixteenth-century Persianate
                           styles. Subsequent 
                           partial over-painting and re-drawing, over the gutters.</p></decoNote> 
                     <decoNote type="headpiece"><p>The headpiece above the title on <locus from="1b">folio
                              1b</locus> bears polychrome floral scrollwork, outlined and surmounted
                           by small vertical radiant lines in blue and abutted by a strapwork chain
                           in gold and blue outlined in bright green and an oxidised dark red lead.</p></decoNote>
                          <decoNote type="lineFill"><p>Initial chapter headings set between pairs of gold floral
                           scrollwork on a blue ground accentuated by dark red dots, and together
                           with the couplets (the <hi rend="italic">basmalla</hi> excepted) 
                           set within outlined cloud-band reserves set against a gold ground, with the
                           gilding accentuated by tiny interstitial punched dots set
                           within a surrounding border of lobed blue half-medallions with palmette
                           scrolls over a gold ground.</p></decoNote> 
                           <decoNote type="marginal"><p>All folios, except for the
                           initial opening, feature light brown stencilling in a two-column
                           format, and marginal ruling
                           framing the text, executed in gold ink outlined in thin black, as well as
                           green, red, and blue.</p></decoNote>
                  </decoDesc>
